For random variables X, Y integrable on (Ω, F, P) and constants a, b ∈ ℝ, the conditional expectation satisfies E[aX + bY | G] = a·E[X | G] + b·E[Y | G] almost surely, for any sub-σ-algebra G ⊆ F. This follows directly from the defining property: Z = E[X | G] is the unique G-measurable random variable satisfying ∫_A Z dP = ∫_A X dP for all A ∈ G. Linearity of the ordinary integral makes a·E[X | G] + b·E[Y | G] satisfy that same defining equation for aX + bY, and G-measurability is preserved under linear combinations. Uniqueness (up to a.s. equality) then gives the result. The property extends by induction to finite sums and, under appropriate integrability (e.g., dominated convergence), to countable sums as well.